) reveals significant convergences between Shia and Sunni scholarly traditions, alongside nuanced interpretive differences rooted in theological frameworks. Both traditions universally affirm the verse’s core message: disbelievers cannot evade divine accountability, and their efforts cannot thwart Allah’s ultimate will. Al-Tabari (Sunni) and Al-Tabrisi (Shia) concur that the verse reassures believers of divine justice, particularly during conflicts like the Battle of Badr, where early Muslims faced overwhelming odds. Ibn Kathir and Al-Tusi both contextualize the verse as a rejection of worldly arrogance, emphasizing Allah’s omnipotence over human stratagems.

Divergences emerge in theological emphasis. Shia commentators like Al-Tabatabai (Al-Mizan) and Al-Qummi link the verse to the concept of *wilayah* (divine guardianship), interpreting disbelievers’ failure as tied to their rejection of divinely appointed leadership (the Ahl al-Bayt). This reflects the Shia view of history as a cosmic struggle between truth (embodied by the Imams) and falsehood. In contrast, Sunni exegetes such as Al-Razi (Mafatih al-Ghayb) and Al-Qurtubi focus on Allah’s direct omnipotence, framing the verse as a universal principle applicable to all who oppose divine guidance, without explicit ties to specific leadership structures. Al-Qurtubi further emphasizes individual moral responsibility, while Al-Tabatabai stresses communal fidelity to divine authority.

These differences stem from distinct theological priorities: Shia tafsir integrates Imamah theology, while Sunni interpretations prioritize Allah’s transcendence and individual accountability. Historically, Shia emphasis on leadership reflects early community struggles over succession, whereas Sunni exegesis developed within broader juridical and theological debates. Both traditions, however, reinforce practical trust in divine justice, shaping communal resilience against oppression—a shared ethical imperative transcending sectarian boundaries.

